""
"O: I think Stone is on the right track here. As the market clamors for more session beers, most brewers have latched onto session IPAs, light lagers, and even some Belgian table beers. The stout category has been largely unexplored in this light. The potential is there for someone to really take hold of that niche in the market. It's a little more difficult though, as the average consumer expects a bigger boned beer out of a stout. I think they need to market this more aggressively as a session beer, and even go so far as to put 'session' on the label. It's the main selling point of the beer and it would prevent confusion among the consumers expecting something bigger. As it stands this is a nice enough drink for what it is. They do a good job of giving it just enough body and keeping the harsher aspects (astringency, etc) in check. It remains to be seen if 'session stouts'  will ever catch on, but if you're going to throw your hat in the ring then go full bore and market the shit out of it as such."
